      "strengths_deep_dive": [
        "Muslim Aid America's financial health is characterized by rapid growth and disciplined spending. Between 2021 and 2023, <cite id=\"10\">revenue grew from $16.9 million to over $26.1 million</cite>, representing a <cite id=\"5\">24.2% compound annual growth rate</cite>. This growth has been matched by a commitment to transparency, as evidenced by their <cite id=\"11\">Candid Platinum Seal of Transparency</cite>. Furthermore, the organization\u2019s <cite id=\"12\">independent board consists of 9 members</cite> with 100% independence, ensuring strong oversight of its <cite id=\"13\">$32.7 million in total grants</cite> distributed globally."
      ],
      "summary": "Muslim Aid America (MAUSA) is a humanitarian relief organization that provides <cite id=\"1\">essential aid to victims of conflict and natural disasters</cite> across the Middle East, Asia, and Africa. The organization operates with a high degree of financial efficiency, reporting <cite id=\"2\">$26,177,076 in total revenue</cite> for the 2023 fiscal year. A defining characteristic of MAUSA is its lean operational model, which directs a <cite id=\"3\">program expense ratio of 93.2%</cite> toward direct service delivery. This ensures that the vast majority of donor contributions are utilized for <cite id=\"4\">emergency relief, water, sanitation, and food security</cite> programs. The organization has demonstrated significant growth, evidenced by a <cite id=\"5\">3-year revenue CAGR of 24.2%</cite>, reflecting increasing donor trust and expanded operational capacity. MAUSA is <cite id=\"6\">verified as Zakat-eligible</cite>, maintaining a dedicated framework to distribute funds across <cite id=\"7\">eight asnaf categories</cite>, including the poor (fuqara) and needy (masakin). While the organization relies heavily on non-cash contributions, its <cite id=\"8\">fundraising efficiency of $0.04 per $1 raised</cite> ranks among the most competitive in the international relief sector.",
